Adapting quantum error-correcting codes (QECCs) to a system's noise profile can enhance their effectiveness, but achieving this adaptation often requires extensive engineering. A cat qubit, encoded in a spin-$F$ system, is a promising candidate for bias-tailored QECCs, as it offers a higher error threshold compared to typical qubits. However, real-world limitations such as the difficulty in performing fast, covariant SU(2) rotations with arbitrary rotation angles and the lack of comprehensive noise characterization in neutral atom platforms can hinder their practical implementation. In this work, single-qubit controls of a spin-cat qubit with nuclear spin $I=5/2$ were demonstrated, achieving a gate fidelity of $0.961 	imes 10^{
u}$ and revealing a bias in idling errors toward dephasing as the encoded sublevel $|m_F|$ increases. The bias of rank-preserving gates was also benchmarked, showing a finite $18 	imes 10^{
u}$ bias compared to the negligible bias in a two-level system of ${}^{171}	ext{Yb}$ ions. These findings demonstrate the feasibility of spin-cat qubits for realizing hardware-efficient quantum error correction, paving the way for fault-tolerant quantum computation using spin-cat codes.
